{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519926"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:17:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:17:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13102"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13102"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.32,0.02,0.02,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5539"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-06-27T15:09:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T03:34:01+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-05-17T19:33:17+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-28 15:30:51"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13102"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94952"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"3996"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5768"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46443"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94952"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old plumber with a private licence was recently investigated for a recent witnessed generalised seizure while off work three weeks ago. He presented to hospital and was discharged after 3 days on Levetiracetam 500mg BD. He said he had a sporting head injury when he was younger but he was checked by a doctor. He has been well with no further seizures and has been taking his medication. A physical examination was normal with no focal neurology. His initial CT brain in hospital was normal and an outpatient MRI Brain demonstrated no intracranial seizure foci. The electroencephalogram (EEG) was abnormal and showed intermittent focal spike and wave activity over the right frontal lobe. A diagnosis of generalised epilepsy was made. The patient is now seeking advice on when he can resume his work as a plumber, which involves driving a private vehicle to and from work.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Considering the fitness to drive, which of the following factors is the most crucial in assessing the patient\u0027s eligibility to return to drive?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The patient\u0027s age and level of experience and skill in operating private vehicles and history of road accidents.","The requirements of the Austroad Guidelines for one unprovoked generalised seizure.","The patient\u0027s inability to earn a living and financial hardship due to the driving restriction (patient unable to drive his car for work as a plumber).","The availability of alternative transportation options for the patient.","The duration of time since the last seizure and adherence to anti-seizure medication since last review"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEpilepsy refers to the tendency for an individual\u0027s brain to experience recurrent seizures. Epilepsy is defined as:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt least two unprovoked seizures occurring more than 24 hours apart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne unprovoked seizure and a probability of further seizures similar to the general recurrence risk after two unprovoked seizures (\u003E60% recurrence rate)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the patient was given the diagnosis of epilepsy with one seizure and the abnormal EEG. The patient has had one seizure and has a diagnosis if epilepsy (As per point 2 above). National Australian law deems that the patient cannot drive for 6 months and can only get clearance for further driving by a Neurologist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGenerally, people with well-managed epilepsy can be considered by the relevant driving authorities to be fit to drive a private vehicle. One of the key components in assessing how well-managed the epilepsy is based on \u003Cstrong\u003Ean appropriate seizure-free period and adherence to their prescribed anti-epileptic medication\u003C/strong\u003E. In this case, the seizure free- period is 6 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst not mandatory, doctors can report patients who they believe are not fit to drive to the driver licensing authority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe patient\u0027s level of experience and skill in operating private vehicles and history of road accidents\u003C/strong\u003E are not assessed in fitness to drive in this scenario. Road accidents would only be assessed in detailed history if there was a seizure or medical event whilst driving.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEpilepsy and driving require knowledge of the legal duties of a doctor when assessing and treating patients. The legal duties include accurate patient education and accurate reporting to transport authorities. \u003Cstrong\u003EThe requirements of the Austroad Guidelines for single unprovoked seizure is incorrect.\u003C/strong\u003E The regulation is for an incorrect seizure presentation, the patient has epilepsy ( a chronic condition) and that would have a different regulation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe patient\u0027s inability to earn a living and financial hardship due to the driving restriction is not a consideration in the medico-legal context of epilepsy and driving.\u003C/strong\u003E Patients must find a way to life with a driving restriction. Social services can provide some assistance if significant financial hardship.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESimilarly, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eavailability of alternative transportation\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptions\u003C/strong\u003E is unrelated to assessing our patient\u0027s fitness to drive. It is the duty of the patient to make arrangements to able live and function.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["When assessing a private driver\u0027s fitness to drive after experiencing a medical event, adherence to medical treatment and the duration since the last episode are crucial factors to consider in addition to accurate driving restriction information from Austroad guidelines.","Clinical care of patients with seizures and/or epilepsy require accurate understanding medico-legal context in relation to driving. Austroad guidelines must be consulted to ensure accuracy of driving restrictions if they are unknown to the practitioner.","Failure to provide accurate advice to patients with seizures or epilepsy is a form of medical malpractice and can result in consequences for the practitioner."],"references":["Austroads. Assessing Fitness to Drive for commercial and private vehicle drivers. Medical standards for licensing and clinical management guidelines. Sydney: Austroads; 2022. Section 6: Neurological conditions - Seizures and epilepsy. Available at: https://austroads.com.au/publications/assessing-fitness-to-drive/ap-g56/neurological-conditions/seizures-and-epilepsy"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94952"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13102"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94952"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T03:32:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T03:33:42+09:30","number":10,"notes":"Updated reference to proper Vancouver format with full citation details including publication title, publisher, year, and specific section information.","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-09-08T03:33:16+09:30","plagiarismScore":11.9,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-5539-10.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T044746Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=1fe68be1842207056e8a8e811c5be7161e67d4837358f47d2930c3590c514547"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5539"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112920"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"generation":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisionGenerations","id":"24731"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"g